GAMs 101

Dataset

This notebook aims at presenting basics of Generalized Additive Models (Hastie & Tibsharani, 1996). We are agoing to focus on fictitious (though probable) data of a subscription business where people sign up for receiving meal boxes.

library.list <- c('mgcv', 'forecast', 'openxlsx', 'ggplot2', 'e1071', 'dplyr', 'tidyr')
lapply(library.list, require, character.only=T)

set.seed = 2018
setwd('~/Documents/MyHF/GAM_tutorial/')
df <- read.xlsx('subscription_demand.xlsx')
df$year.num <- c(rep(1, 52), rep(2, nrow(df)-52))
df$year <- as.factor(paste0('Year', df$year.num))

Our dataset consists of 5 predictors and a target (sales) in form of number of boxes to be shipped each week. Our planned predictors are measured 4 weeks in advance, simply as number of people who plan to churn, pause their subscription or receive a box as usual. Additionally, we will be looking at: - holiday effect: note this is a continuous and normalized variable, aggregting effects of seasonality and one-time events - trend: a variable denoting baseline trend of sales, computed on all data available until t-1 for moment t0; also normalized

Interestingly, no clear time-related effects can easily be spotted within our target which suggests that forecasting based on traditional time-series methods (like ARIMAx) might not prove to be the best option.

Basic GAM

Lets start with a simple split into train & test. On train set well build a basic GAM, letting the package choose number of knots and going with default smooth settings (tp - thin plate splines).

rr df.train <- df[1:87,] demand.gam.model <- gam(sales ~ s(holiday.effect) + s(planned_sales) + s(planned_pauses) + s(planned_churn) + + s(trend), data = df.train, control=gam.control(mgcv.tol=1e-4)) summary(demand.gam.model)

Smooths & regularization

A large set of smooth options is available. Most common include: - thin plate splines (tp) - B-splines (bs) - a subset of B-splines: cubic regression splines (cr or shrunk version, cs)

See what happens if we switch to cubic splines:

rr demand.gam.model <- gam(sales ~ s(holiday.effect, bs=cr) + s(planned_sales, bs=cr) + s(planned_pauses, bs=cr) + s(planned_churn, bs=cr) + + s(trend, bs=cr), data = df.train, control=gam.control(mgcv.tol=1e-4)) summary(demand.gam.model)

We can use regularization, either via a penalty applied to all terms with select=T or using a shrinkage version of smooths.

rr demand.gam.model <- gam(sales ~ s(holiday.effect, bs=cr) + s(planned_sales, bs=cr) + s(planned_pauses, bs=cr) + s(planned_churn, bs=cr) + + s(trend, bs=cr), data = df.train, control=gam.control(mgcv.tol=1e-4), select=T) summary(demand.gam.model)

If nature of our relation between predictors and target changes over time, we can introduce a by variable.

rr spline.type <- cs demand.gam.model <- gam(sales ~ year + s(holiday.effect, bs=spline.type, by=year) + s(planned_sales, bs=spline.type) + s(planned_pauses, bs=spline.type) + s(planned_churn, bs=spline.type) + + s(trend, bs=spline.type, by=year), data = df.train, control=gam.control(mgcv.tol=1e-4)) summary(demand.gam.model)

Marketing attribution

Some models require applying shape constraints so that we get non-negative impact of channels. Then new splines can be used, e.g: - mpi - monotonic increasing penalized B-splines - micv - monotonic convex increasing B-splines etc. Typically shape constraints result in underfitting .

rr scam.spline.type = mpi #marketing.data\(Weekday.factor <- as.factor(marketing.data\)Weekday) mrktg.scam <- scam(Conversions ~ s(TVSpend, bs = scam.spline.type) + s(Facebook, bs = scam.spline.type) + s(Affiliate, bs = scam.spline.type) + s(SEM.nonbrand, bs = scam.spline.type) + s(SEM.brand, bs = scam.spline.type) + Xmas.flag + s(Weekday, k=7), data = marketing.data) summary(mrktg.scam)
